segments.text: This is the 22nd of February.
Looks like perhaps it might rain outside.
In the former student building, interviewing Ed Cooper, the second of what may be a number of interviews.
Ed, try yours now.
OK.
Here I am in the library at the alumni office talking at a regular tone.
We chatted with earlier about your student experiences Let's begin today when you came to College Station after serving in the extension service actually
My first job, I was assistant county agricultural agent in Travis County, Austin, Texas.
And that was just for a brief tour of duty to get a feel of what county agricultural agent work was all about.
I had just returned from Germany as a lieutenant in the 2nd Armored Division, a tank platoon leader.
And they put me in training in Austin.
When Mr. Callender retired, I spent seven years as extension specialist in wildlife conservation and traveled all over the state.
Some of my best memories of people in Texas occurred during those years.
Then I left extension to get wealthy.
That did not work.
And I got a call from Clark C. Monroe, who was personnel director.
That was the title.
I wondered if I would interview as a prospect for President Rutter's assistant.
Darcy McCrory had become director of development.
That wasn't the title at the time, but that's what it was, fundraising.
And I went in to Darcy.
I'm getting ahead of myself.
I went, I agreed to an interview.
I was scared.

I was afraid of Mr. Rutter as a lot of people were because here's an Army general and highly decorated veteran and I really didn't know what to expect and cold steel looking eyes and penetrating gaze and he looked me over and he says, Cooper, I understand that you sell limestone.
I said, yes, sir, that's our business.
And he said, would you make a good deal for me?
I said, sure.
Where do you want it?
He said, well, it's between London and Hex, Texas.
I said, you're talking about the hill country.
I said, the whole thing is limestone.
I don't think you really need it.
And he just died laughing.
And that's the way it started, and it got better from there.
And I think with my military background and having come from the little town of San Marcos, things like that influenced him.
I had been in the band and things like that, and I'd done some things that he paralleled with in some ways.
What seemed to be his greatest concerns in that first conversation?
We didn't...
We didn't get into any substantial subject matter discussions at all, or as they would say these days, issues.
There was no hint of that.
I think his whole strategy, as he told me later, was to scope me out as an individual checking out my
personal likes, dislikes, experiences, that kind of thing.

I remember years later I was talking to him while I was on his staff about a faculty member that was really, can I use real language, really making an ass out of himself about two or three little things.
And he just kept on.
And I said,
Why does the world have people like that?
He said, well, when you hire someone, he said, no one is perfect.
He said, find out very quickly what they do well at, keep them focused completely on that, and don't let them get out in the left or right field where they can't handle it.
You can't expect them to do it if they're not inclined to do it,
He said, so the secret to success and having people work for you is have them do what they're good at, and I don't really care what he says.
He's a good professor.
Now, you were not acquainted with him other than very casually before.
That's right.
I'd seen him at a distance.
We hit it off, and a very short time later, I got back to Jacksonville, where I was living,
In other words, I felt good about the interview.
I felt he made me feel comfortable.
He knew how to do that.
And I think, to me, that's a trait of a great man, that they can find out what level you're at and they can adjust and bring themselves into that level so that good conversation takes place.
But he wasn't scoping me out on anything like coeducation or integration or anything like that that came up while I was working for him.
But I went to Dorsey McCrory as he left his office, and I said, Dorsey, tell me how to be a good assistant to the president.
And he looked at me and smiled.
He said, well, you'll find out.
and said, I'll see you later, and he walked out.
That was my total training for this job.
Now, the selection, your being selected for this job occurred when?
I was in that job four years.
So we were right at the decision time for coeducation, voluntary core, and all that.
That's right.
Those things were already rumbling.
And the things that, the big issues that came up in high school while I was in his office, to me the big issues were changing the name from Agricultural Mechanical College to Texas A&M University.
The admission of black students.
Of course, we'd had Hispanic for all time.
That was never even an issue.
The admission of female students and making the core non-compulsory.
As much as, as close as he and I were,
There are some things that I never did really understand about him, and the main one was how he really felt about the admission of women.
I thought I could read him, and he would say something one time that would make me think, well, he's for this, and then he'd say something else.
He would kind of sway with whoever he was talking with,
about that subject.

And of the four that I just mentioned, girls, blacks, name change, non-compulsory, of those four things, the women issue, the woman issue, was so far ahead of the others that they were just left in the dust.
I recall reports, I've talked with Mrs. Rutter about this too, the papers reported that when
There was a threat of girls coming to A&M.
People were sending in diplomas by the suitcase full and senior rings and nasty letters.
If they came in, Haskell, I didn't see them.
I remember one torn-up diploma, and I remember one senior ring that was sent by.
And I found out later that the man had gotten so big he couldn't wear the ring anymore anyway.
But...
there were three or four redneck Aggies, I call them, one in Beaumont, one in Dallas.
And I'll not call names, but they stirred up a considerable amount of controversy.
And it's like the crowd that said, give us Barnabas.
That was something that a lot of people wanted to say but didn't have the courage to say.
My mother, bless her heart,
felt very strongly against coeducation.
And I often wish that I could take her back across the campus and show her what has happened.
She's gone.
She lived to be 94, but she never was sold on that subject because she remembered A&M in the good old days when the boys wore gray and the girls weren't around to confuse us.
One day in a conversation not recorded,
You shared with me an idea that you, where you thought there was a person that Mr. Rutter had known a long time in politics that may have encouraged him.
As far as the change goes?
Yes.
Yes.
That little story is, and he told me that when he went to Washington, while after Mr. Johnson became president, which was what, 63?
Mm-hmm.

If he found out that Earl Rudder had been in town and spent some time without spending the night at the White House, he would get a nasty telephone call because they, well of course he was his West Texas campaign manager.
It hurt his feelings when Mr. Rutter would go to town and not go by.
And so one time he went and I believe it was the same trip where he had this conversation that is urgently important.
I believe it was the same trip.
An emergency came up that required Mr. Johnson's attention on end of the night.
And President Rutter said, well, we're not going to get to have a drink and talk politics tonight.
And I read in the paper where Fiddler on the Roof is showing at a theater near the White House.
And so he got permission and left, took in the movie.
And about 5 the next morning, the phone rang.
And he said, goddammit, Rutter.
He said, you're a guest of the President of the United States, and you won't even stay here and drink whiskey with him after work's over.
And I think it was that trip or very close to it.
And Mr.
Rudder did not always tell me.
He didn't have time or inclination.
He didn't always tell me all of the personalities, all of the stuff that was going on.
It's just impossible.
So I was not privy to a lot of things that...
because of the nature of the job that I had, a lot of big things that were going on.
But on this particular thing, he said that he talked with President Johnson.
He said, Lyndon, they're talking about integration, changing the name, making the core non-compulsory, and of all things, letting girls in our school.
And the board would have to make that decision.
He said, but I'd be right in the middle of it, of course.
He said, what do you think?
And he said, two of the things you're talking about, I don't think anyone in Washington cares about.
But there are two things you're talking about that we do care about.
one is equal opportunity for girls, one is equal opportunity for black people.
He said, if you move into those right now, you can do it in your style and your way.
If you don't, we'll do it for you.
And I don't think you'll like the way we're going to do it.
So with that message,
He was able to come back and meet with some key alumni officials, former students, through the board and said, listen, fellas, here's the way it is.
Now, if you want to fight that thing, tooth and toenail, we can do it, but we're going to be made laughing stock.
The big man has said that the feds are going to do it for us.
If we don't do it our way, could you get the word out
to where the hell is being raised and let them know where we really stand.
And suddenly things got quiet.
And I remember, if I'm not mistaken, the Winter Council meeting is the one where a resolution had been drafted to support the board in these moves.
And I can't remember whether it was all in the same document or not.
I'm not sure about that.
My memory's not that good.
But the main one, of course, was girls.
And if I'm not mistaken, John Lindsay was president that year.
And if my memory is correct, the board of directors, as we then call the regents, and the association board met the same day.
And there was a quick approval, and they went down the hallway quickly.
Yeah, they were in the same building.
Right.
They were in the, the council meeting was in the, what we call the assembly room or something else now.
But I remember I was in the room and the resolution was raised and John Lindsay was about the color of your shirt, afraid of a bomb, you know, blowing up there at the meeting.
And I think there had been discussions about who would make the motion.

and who would second it and it happened like a shot in the dark and the gavel was slammed and he said motion approved and uh and he he got off that that hot stool probably the hottest one he's ever been on and and from then on really uh it was a foregone conclusion and then you'll remember of course all of the how the legislature got involved in it
And that was a very unpleasant kind of a thing.
And there was all sorts of attempts to sway people one way or the other.
And they had an open forum on the subject on the floor of the house.
And people made impassioned speeches.
And it was not well handled.
And I don't remember all the specifics of who did what.
I do remember that...
There was even a little hanky-panky involved, trade-offs, and I'll not mention who that involved.
Now, our local legislators were strongly in favor of the changes.
Yes, yes.
And that would have been Senator Bill Moore.
Right.
Was it David Haynes?
No, no.
Presnell?
No, before him.
Before Haynes even?
Yeah, a quiet guy.
Oh, was it Brownrig Dewey?
Brownrig Dewey.
Yeah, later came in and was Justice of the Peaks.
That's right.
Yeah, Brownrig Dewey, that's right.
He preceded Haynes, and then Haynes was...

personal came in after Hank on the board of directors then as far as you can recall who were the key first broad question who were the most powerful most potent members of the board of directors at that time Sterling Evans and of course things that you and I
cherished here, he was largely responsible for above and beyond that.
But he honestly felt deep in his heart about coeducation.
All right, let me offer his answer.
I asked him, when did he favor coeducation?
And he said, what do you mean?
I said, when did you start believing that girls ought to be at A&M?
And he grinned and said, when I got here as a 17-year-old boy.
And there weren't any.
He said, I have always been for coeducation.
Sterling Evans, to me, I saw great people on that board of directors back there.
Dr. Boyle.
from Dow Chemical in his precise German ways would bring the first handheld computers I've ever seen.
And they'd be up talking about construction costs and financing and interest rates and all.
And he'd say, you're off a little bit on that, aren't you?
And he was checking them out as they spoke.
And the man that was president of Tennessee Gas
Not Cain.
No.
Not Orford Cain.
Oh, it'll come to me before we're through.
But there were some sure enough good people on there.
Of course, Clyde Wills had been on there forever.
All right.
Al Davies and Dick Goodson come along somewhere about that time.
That's right.
Sears and Southwestern Bell.
Right.
And the man with Hart Hanks, the...
Man from Amarillo, Amarillo Globe News.
Those names now are getting fuzzy with me.
We can identify those.
But L.F. Peterson was in there.
As far as my memory, the man from Boydle and Evans and the guy with Tennessee Gas, good gracious.
They were really super players, and they didn't have axes to grind.
They wanted to do what was right.
And when they would come to town, and there'd be these little sessions before the board meeting, the directors would say to President Rutter,
What do you want us to do for you at this meeting?
And since then, it has not always been that way.
Now you're inferring that they gave evidence that they thought their task was to help the institution.
not to micromanage it.
That's correct.
As far as you're aware, with those big issues, those four big issues, who was the most outspoken opponent on the board, if there was one?
The guy from, this is not in response to that question, but Sam Wittenberg was the man from Amarillo.
He was, I mean, he was top notch.
He didn't attend all the meetings, but he was here.
But I was not aware of an individual on the board
that was vociferous about those issues.
If there were, I don't know who it would be.
I don't remember any newspaper discussion of there being a divided vote.
It seemed to me as an outsider that whatever differences of opinion there were, they resolved them.
and gave publicly the appearance of unanimity.
That's correct.
And of course things go on in chambers that you and I would never have access to and no one would ever talk about.
So it may have been a rougher road to hoe than I know about, but I think I would have heard something about it.
And we didn't have open meetings law then.
No, we did not.
In my interview with Vice President Wayne Hull, then the Chief Academic Officer,
he indicated that he is the one who thought up the name as it now is with the A&M with no periods, no abbreviations.

He said that it was his recollection that Mr. Rutter was very much bothered by the proposed name of Texas State University and that he wanted the A&M and that he, Hall, came up with that and Mr. Rutter liked that.
I don't remember that particular thing.
But I do remember his resentment of Texas State University.
He did not like that.
He was enough.
I think his idea at Haskell was that we're taking away some things from some people that really are near and dear to us.
Let's don't take it all.
Let's leave the symbolic part.

name of the place at least and so uh but this is what he was good at and of course that's what lyndon johnson was good at he would uh he knew how to compromise now uh once in a conversation with mr rutter early in 19 calendar 1970 i said to him mr rudder only you could have done that although made those changes he grinned and he said why do you say that and i then kind of made a list

Verbally, I said, sir, they couldn't say you weren't a Texan, you weren't an Aggie, you hadn't been in the Corps, you hadn't served your country, that you're one of those fuddy-duddy PhDs from somewhere way off in the Northeast.
And he smiled and he said, oh, I never thought of any of that.
His smile gave me the impression that he had a great deal.
What I'm leading to is a question.
Did his background...
of being a Texan and an Aggie, do you recall that that was very positive in his being able to make those changes occur?
Yes.
Well, of course, he's a hill country boy.
He worked hard all his life.
He was from humble beginnings.
He got into the land commissioner's job by being close to.
He had attributes across the board that were positive in his background and his experience.
And, of course, his war record just enhanced all of that.
But I can't think of anything that would have been negative.
If you say to someone from Texas, wherever you are,

geographically you say well he's he's an old hill country boy they know what you're talking about and there's some kind of a positive connotation with that maybe it's because it's the heart of Texas or it is a part of Texas that everybody loves but there's kind of a feeling that if he grew up there some of the goodness of it had to rub off on him
All right, let's mention some of the other relationships.
What was his relationship with our congressman at that time?
The congressman?
I asked my Sunday school class the other day.
We were talking about Timothy and his role going to Philippi
at Paul's request to satisfy some problems at the church.
The man had humility and the deepest faith that anyone could imagine, and that's why Paul sent him out.
While he was in jail, he was most of the time.
But I asked this class the other day, I said, now name me a person right now, either in Austin or Washington, that you would describe as one of great

humility and anxiety to serve with no selfish motive who is that person and I said I knew such a person and I would have called his name if you would have asked me that it was Olenny Teague I said he would comb his hair ten years after the war and pieces of shrapnel would come out with a comb and he would come up to me and

after not having seen me for a while and kind of waddled up and put his hand out way before he got to me and his words were always the same, Edwin Cooper or Ed Cooper, what can I do for you today and how is Peggy and all those kids.
I see Congressman Teague and Mr. Rutter as being in many ways

peas out of the same pod they had the same strong conviction about America and about Texas and about doing things right and I think they honestly both had the spirit of what I think is one of the best logos of any civic club in the world namely Rotary when an issue comes up and a decision has to be made
What is it that will do the most good for the most people for the longest period of time?
Now, how can you improve on that?
And I really believe that both those men felt that way.
They loved to tease each other.
Tiger loved to tell a story about the cow that wouldn't give enough milk, and Mr.
Rudder would water it down, and he'd counterattack with his high-level jaw about it.
Sheep barn shoveling manure and stuff like that.
But they truly and honestly admired and respected each other.
They were playing off the same page.
I remember one day Mr.
Rudder came up to me and said, Listen, Tiger's coming in.
He's going to be over in the lobby of the MSC at 1.30.
Then he expects me to be there.
Something's come up.
I cannot be there.
And he handed me a roll of $50 bills, I think.
I believe there were eight of them.
And he said, when you shake hands with Tiger, have that palm in your hand and don't tell him who it came from.
He said, the man that gave it to me doesn't want him to know.
And I shook hands with Tiger.
And of course, he felt the money.
He looked down.
He didn't say a word.
He just kept on talking.
But there was that.
well-understood interchange of things political that happened between two people like that.
That's what makes the world go round.
But they were very much alike in their temperament.
Olin E. Teague never came to College Station without telling President Rutter when he'd be here and when they could get together.
And they would set up late hours.
They'd have a drink or two and talk about what it was in Washington, what it was in College Station that were issues of the day.
And then the then comparatively young new governor and his wife, I understand, had been classmates of Mrs. Rutter at the University of Texas.
What was the relationship of President Rutter with Governor Conley?
Their roots went back a good ways.
And it was first name basis.
I remember the governor was here after having been shot in the parade at Dallas, not too long afterwards.
And we had, we met, we, Mr.
Rudder and Mr.

the vice presidents and all, they formed an honor guard with the RVs with the swords at that west entry down to where the board quarters are now of the MSC and the boys gave, present arms and raised their swords and here we were at one end waiting for them to come through and Connolly flinched as if he was scared
when the swords were drawn, and he was teasing.
He just did like that, you know.
And when he got to Mr. Rutter, he held his arm out, and he said, Earl, don't twist my arm.
It still hurts.
And then they went into one of those rooms that was reserved for regents, I think.
That's before they had their own quarters.
And they talked for hours in there.
And he was here to, it might have been a commencement speech, but...
When you consider the political arena of
